</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-33_ pf-text-1"><strong>First aid </strong>- Is the initial assistance or treatment given to someone suffering from injury or illness before professional medical help arrives.





















</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-35_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fXEqDS hwCMhq pf-36_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-ctqQKy eJZCTA pf-37_ pf-heading-1-h3">Legislation, regulations, and best practice</h3><p class="sc-dFtzxp kOHCjr pf-39_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>In the United Kingdom, employers must comply with the Health and Safety (First Aid) Regulations 1981, which outline the legal requirements for first aid provision in the workplace. While these regulations may not directly apply to caregivers at home, adhering to similar standards ensures a safe environment for infants.

<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-41_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fXEqDS hwCMhq pf-42_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-ctqQKy eJZCTA pf-43_ pf-heading-1-h3">Recognising signs of illness</h3><p class="sc-dFtzxp kOHCjr pf-45_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>Understanding common signs of illness in infants is crucial for early intervention. Symptoms such as persistent crying, fever, difficulty breathing, or changes in skin colour should prompt immediate attention.


<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-47_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fXEqDS hwCMhq pf-48_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-ctqQKy eJZCTA pf-49_ pf-heading-1-h3">Basic first aid procedures</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-cbTzjv cdRhtw pf-51_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-52_ pf-text-1"><strong>Fever management</strong> - Use a digital thermometer to measure the baby's temperature. Administer infant-appropriate fever-reducing medication as per medical advice.















</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-54_ pf-text-1"><strong>Choking</strong> - If the baby is conscious but choking, perform back blows and chest thrusts following infant CPR guidelines.























</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-56_ pf-text-1"><strong>Breathing difficulties</strong> - Place the baby in a position that aids breathing, such as lying on its side with its head tilted back slightly.
























</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-58_ pf-text-1"><strong>Seizures</strong> - Keep the baby safe from nearby hazards and gently cushion their head. Do not restrain their movements, and time the duration of the seizure.

























</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-60_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fXEqDS hwCMhq pf-61_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-ctqQKy eJZCTA pf-62_ pf-heading-1-h3">Recommendations</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-cbTzjv cdRhtw pf-64_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-hjGZqJ gtgMXo pf-65_ pf-text-1">Enrol in a certified infant first aid course endorsed by reputable organisations to gain practical skills and confidence in handling emergencies.
















